“’Щ@6ad216b51e7504df8f803acd045e530e229514d6fed861557c56e2abe4ae10afЪoTitle: title: Files
Path: Editing a file and then saving the changes
Content:
Here we are making edits to 
``Cargo.toml``
. We increase the patch version of the crate using 
``inc``
 and then save it back to the file.

Use 
``help inc``
 to get more information.
Read the file's initial contents
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open Cargo.toml | get package.version

```
Output
``0.59.0``
Make the edit to the version number and save it.
Note: running this command should work but it will reorder the toml file alphabetically by section.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open Cargo.toml | upsert package.version { |p| $p | get package.version | inc --patch } | save -f Cargo.toml

```
Note: 
``inc``
 is available through the plugin 
``nu_plugin_inc``
.
Output

none
View the changes we made to the file.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open Cargo.toml | get package.version

```
Output
``0.59.1``
’Щ@a39385d6be805536e2269c17c82406c320737ada333b62c78c7e8b858f02e1a7Ъ„Title: title: Files
Path: Parsing a file in a non-standard format
Content:
Suppose you have a file with the following format.
```Fenced(Borrowed("text"))
band:album:year
Fugazi:Steady Diet of Nothing:1991
Fugazi:The Argument:2001
Fugazi:7 Songs:1988
Fugazi:Repeater:1990
Fugazi:In On The Kill Taker:1993

```
You can parse it into a table.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open bands.txt | lines | split column ":" Band Album Year | skip 1 | sort-by Year
# => в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Їв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Їв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Їв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓ
# =>  # в”‚ Band   в”‚ Album                  в”‚ Year
# => в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
# =>  0 в”‚ Fugazi в”‚ 7 Songs                в”‚ 1988
# =>  1 в”‚ Fugazi в”‚ Repeater               в”‚ 1990
# =>  2 в”‚ Fugazi в”‚ Steady Diet of Nothing в”‚ 1991
# =>  3 в”‚ Fugazi в”‚ In On The Kill Taker   в”‚ 1993
# =>  4 в”‚ Fugazi в”‚ The Argument           в”‚ 2001
# => в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”·в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”·в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”·в”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓв”Ѓ

```
You can alternatively do this using 
``parse``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open bands.txt | lines | parse "{Band}:{Album}:{Year}" | skip 1 | sort-by Year

```
Or, you can utilize the 
``headers``
 command to use the first row as a header row. The only difference would be the headers would match the case of the text file. So, in this case, the headers would be lowercase.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
open bands.txt | lines | split column ":" | headers | sort-by year

```
’Щ@df7aef0cf95302f41523afe9b3cfee6d8b5ac424b250b02e4ba31b305ecf6f06ЪcTitle: title: Files
Path: Word occurrence count with Ripgrep
Content:
Suppose you would like to check the number of lines the string "Value" appears per file in the nushell project, then sort those files by largest line count.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
rg -c Value | lines | split column ":" file line_count | into int line_count | sort-by line_count | reverse
# => в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”¬в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
# =>  # в”‚ file                                 в”‚ line_count
# => в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”јв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
# =>  0 в”‚ crates/nu-source/src/meta.rs         в”‚         27
# =>  1 в”‚ crates/nu-protocol/src/value/dict.rs в”‚         10
# =>  2 в”‚ src/commands/config.rs               в”‚         10
# =>  3 в”‚ crates/nu_plugin_sys/src/sys.rs      в”‚         10
# =>  4 в”‚ src/commands/from_bson.rs            в”‚          9
# =>  5 в”‚ src/utils/data_processing.rs         в”‚          9
# =>  6 в”‚ src/deserializer.rs                  в”‚          8
# =>  7 в”‚ src/commands/histogram.rs            в”‚          7
# =>  8 в”‚ src/commands/split_column.rs         в”‚          6
# =>  9 в”‚ src/data/dict.rs                     в”‚          6
# => в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”ґв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
# => ... example output limited due to large output

```
